<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch06-identical-particles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Identical Particles and Many-Body Systems (Dimension 3)</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand the quantum indistinguishability of identical particles and its profound consequences.</li>
      <li>Master symmetric and antisymmetric wavefunctions and their physical interpretations.</li>
      <li>Apply the Pauli exclusion principle rigorously using Slater determinants.</li>
      <li>Understand the connection between particle statistics and spin via the spin-statistics theorem.</li>
      <li>Analyze two-particle and few-particle systems systematically.</li>
      <li>Build intuition for collective phenomena emerging from many-body physics.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p>The third dimension of the framework asks how many particles the system contains. But distinguishing this from the single-particle case reveals one of the most profound features of quantum mechanics: identical particles are indistinguishable. This is not merely an artifact of our lack of experimental resolution, but a fundamental feature of quantum theory. Two electrons are not "labeled" in any meaningful sense; their wavefunctions must reflect this indistinguishability through specific symmetry properties. This chapter develops the mathematics and physics of identical particles, from the simplest two-particle case to the structure of many-body systems.</p>
  </introduction>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-indistinguishability">
    <title>Indistinguishability and Exchange Symmetry</title>
    <p>In classical mechanics, particles are distinguishable. We can track electron #1 and electron #2 separately, label them, and compute their trajectories. In quantum mechanics, this is impossible. The wavefunctions are defined over abstract Hilbert space; there is no label attached to a particle.</p>
    <p>Consider two particles in states <m>\ket{\psi_1}</m> and <m>\ket{\psi_2}</m>. Classically, the joint state would be ordered: particle 1 in state <m>\psi_1</m> and particle 2 in state <m>\psi_2</m>. Quantum mechanically, we write this as <m>\ket{\psi_1(1), \psi_2(2)}</m>. But swapping the particles—particle 1 in state <m>\psi_2</m> and particle 2 in state <m>\psi_1</m>—must be treated with care.</p>
    <p>Define the <em>exchange operator</em> or <em>permutation operator</em> <m>\mathcal{P}_{12}</m> which swaps the two particles:</p>
    <me>
      \mathcal{P}_{12} \ket{\psi_1(1), \psi_2(2)} = \ket{\psi_1(2), \psi_2(1)} = \ket{\psi_2(1), \psi_1(2)}.
    </me>
    <p>This operator is its own inverse: <m>\mathcal{P}_{12}^2 = \II</m>. Therefore, its eigenvalues are <m>\pm 1</m>. The eigenstates are either symmetric or antisymmetric under particle exchange.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-symmetric-antisymmetric">
    <title>Symmetric and Antisymmetric States</title>
    <p>For two particles in states <m>\ket{a}</m> and <m>\ket{b}</m> (with <m>a \ne b</m>), the properly symmetrized wavefunctions are:</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\psi_+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\ket{a(1), b(2)} + \ket{b(1), a(2)}\right)
    </me>
    <p>and</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\psi_-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\ket{a(1), b(2)} - \ket{b(1), a(2)}\right).
    </me>
    <p>The state <m>\ket{\psi_+}</m> is symmetric under exchange: <m>\mathcal{P}_{12}\ket{\psi_+} = \ket{\psi_+}</m>. The state <m>\ket{\psi_-}</m> is antisymmetric: <m>\mathcal{P}_{12}\ket{\psi_-} = -\ket{\psi_-}</m>.</p>
    <p>This is the key: <em>identical bosons require symmetric wavefunctions, and identical fermions require antisymmetric wavefunctions</em>. This is not an assumption but a consequence of relativistic quantum field theory (the spin-statistics theorem).</p>
    <example xml:id="ex-ch06-two-electrons">
      <title>Two Electrons in a Box</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider two electrons in a one-dimensional infinite square well, each with wavefunctions <m>\psi_n(x) = \sqrt{2/L}\sin(n\pi x/L)</m>. If one is in state <m>n=1</m> and the other in state <m>n=2</m>, the properly antisymmetrized wavefunction is</p>
        <me>
          \Psi(x_1, x_2) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\psi_1(x_1)\psi_2(x_2) - \psi_2(x_1)\psi_1(x_2)].
        </me>
        <p>Notice that this vanishes when <m>x_1 = x_2</m>: two electrons cannot be at the same location. This is a direct consequence of the Pauli exclusion principle encoded in the antisymmetry.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-pauli-principle">
    <title>The Pauli Exclusion Principle</title>
    <p>The most dramatic consequence of antisymmetry is the Pauli exclusion principle: <em>no two fermions can occupy the same quantum state</em>.</p>
    <p>Why? If both particles were in state <m>\ket{a}</m>, the antisymmetric wavefunction would be</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\psi_-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{a(1), a(2)} - \ket{a(1), a(2)}) = 0.
    </me>
    <p>The state vanishes: it is unphysical. This is not a constraint imposed externally but an automatic consequence of the mathematical structure of identical fermions.</p>
    <p>This principle has enormous consequences:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>Atomic structure:</em> Electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing energy (the aufbau principle), with at most two per orbital (spin-up and spin-down).</li>
      <li><em>Chemistry:</em> The periodic table emerges from electron shell structure.</li>
      <li><em>Nuclear physics:</em> Nucleons fill nuclear shells, explaining nuclear stability and magic numbers.</li>
      <li><em>Solid-state physics:</em> Electron bands and Fermi surfaces are consequences of antisymmetry.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-slater-determinant">
    <title>Slater Determinants: Systematic Antisymmetrization</title>
    <p>For <m>N</m> fermions in states <m>\ket{a}, \ket{b}, \ket{c}, \ldots</m>, the properly antisymmetrized wavefunction is represented as a Slater determinant:</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\Psi} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{N!}} \begin{vmatrix}
      \psi_a(1) &amp; \psi_b(1) &amp; \psi_c(1) &amp; \cdots \\
      \psi_a(2) &amp; \psi_b(2) &amp; \psi_c(2) &amp; \cdots \\
      \psi_a(3) &amp; \psi_b(3) &amp; \psi_c(3) &amp; \cdots \\
      \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots
      \end{vmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>The determinant automatically enforces antisymmetry: swapping any two rows (corresponding to two particles) changes the sign, and having two identical rows (two particles in the same state) makes the determinant vanish.</p>
    <p>Slater determinants are the standard representation in Hartree-Fock theory, quantum chemistry, and nuclear structure calculations. They provide an organized way to build many-body antisymmetric states from single-particle wavefunctions.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-bosons">
    <title>Bosons and the Symmetry Principle</title>
    <p>For <m>N</m> identical bosons, wavefunctions must be symmetric under all permutations. The simplest case is a product state where all bosons occupy the same single-particle state <m>\ket{a}</m>:</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\Psi} = \ket{a(1)}\ket{a(2)}\cdots\ket{a(N)}.
    </me>
    <p>This is allowed—unlike fermions, many bosons can occupy the same state. This leads to spectacular phenomena:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>Bose-Einstein condensation:</em> At sufficiently low temperature, a macroscopic fraction of bosons occupy the ground state.</li>
      <li><em>Superfluidity:</em> Quantum flows without viscosity.</li>
      <li><em>Lasers:</em> Stimulated emission from identical photons.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For the two-boson case, the symmetric wavefunction is</p>
    <me>
      \ket{\psi_+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{a(1), b(2)} + \ket{b(1), a(2)}),
    </me>
    <p>or simply <m>\ket{a(1), a(2)}</m> if both are in the same state.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-exchange-interaction">
    <title>The Exchange Interaction</title>
    <p>Indistinguishability has a surprising consequence: it produces an effective interaction even when particles don't directly interact. This is the <em>exchange interaction</em>.</p>
    <p>Consider two electrons in states <m>\psi_1</m> and <m>\psi_2</m> with no direct Coulomb repulsion. Classically, the potential energy is zero. Quantum mechanically, the antisymmetric wavefunction</p>
    <me>
      \Psi_-(x_1, x_2) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\psi_1(x_1)\psi_2(x_2) - \psi_2(x_1)\psi_1(x_2)]
    </me>
    <p>has <m>\Psi_-(x_1, x_2) \approx 0</m> when <m>x_1 \approx x_2</m>, while the symmetric wavefunction has <m>\Psi_+(x_1, x_2) \gg 0</m>. The antisymmetric state keeps electrons farther apart on average, lowering their (Coulomb) energy. This is exchange energy, and it is responsible for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>Ferromagnetism:</em> Spins align when exchange coupling is favorable.</li>
      <li><em>Paramagnetism:</em> Opposite regime.</li>
      <li><em>Chemical bonding:</em> The exchange energy in molecular orbitals drives covalent bonding.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-fock-space">
    <title>Fock Space: Many-Body Representation</title>
    <p>For systems with variable or large particle numbers, Fock space is the natural framework. The Fock space for non-relativistic quantum mechanics is</p>
    <me>
      \mathcal{F} = \bigoplus_{N=0}^{\infty} \mathcal{H}_N,
    </me>
    <p>where <m>\mathcal{H}_N</m> is the <m>N</m>-particle Hilbert space, properly symmetrized (bosons) or antisymmetrized (fermions).</p>
    <p>A state in Fock space specifies the occupation number for each single-particle state. For instance, <m>|n_1, n_2, n_3, \ldots\rangle</m> means <m>n_1</m> particles in state 1, <m>n_2</m> in state 2, etc. For fermions, <m>n_i \in \{0, 1\}</m>; for bosons, <m>n_i \in \{0, 1, 2, \ldots\}</m>.</p>
    <p>Creation and annihilation operators <m>a^\dagger_i</m> and <m>a_i</m> add and remove particles from state <m>i</m>. They satisfy</p>
    <me>
      [a_i, a_j^\dagger]_{\pm} = \delta_{ij}, \quad [a_i, a_j]_{\pm} = 0, \quad [a_i^\dagger, a_j^\dagger]_{\pm} = 0,
    </me>
    <p>where <m>[\cdot,\cdot]_-</m> is the commutator (bosons) and <m>\{\cdot,\cdot\}</m> is the anticommutator (fermions). The number operator <m>n_i = a_i^\dagger a_i</m> counts particles in state <m>i</m>.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-mean-field">
    <title>Mean-Field Approximations: Hartree and Hartree-Fock</title>
    <p>For <m>N</m>-particle systems, the exact ground state and dynamics are generally intractable. Mean-field theory provides powerful approximations by treating each particle as moving in the average potential of all others.</p>
    <p><em>Hartree approximation:</em> Each particle is in a self-consistent mean field. The variational ground state is a product of single-particle wavefunctions.</p>
    <p><em>Hartree-Fock approximation:</em> The ground state is a Slater determinant. Electrons move in a mean field that includes exchange effects. This is the starting point for most modern quantum chemistry calculations.</p>
    <p>Both are exact only for non-interacting particles but provide excellent starting points for perturbation theory and provide insight into the structure of atoms, molecules, and nuclear matter.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch06-summary">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>Identical particles are fundamentally indistinguishable in quantum mechanics; wavefunctions must respect exchange symmetry.</li>
      <li>Fermions require antisymmetric wavefunctions; bosons require symmetric ones.</li>
      <li>The Pauli exclusion principle emerges automatically: no two fermions can occupy identical quantum states.</li>
      <li>Slater determinants provide a systematic way to build antisymmetric states for multiple fermions.</li>
      <li>Exchange interaction—an effective attraction for antisymmetric configurations—drives ferromagnetism and chemical bonding.</li>
      <li>Fock space is the natural framework for systems with variable particle number, using creation and annihilation operators.</li>
      <li>Mean-field approximations (Hartree, Hartree-Fock) provide powerful tools for understanding many-body systems.</li>
      <li>The spin-statistics theorem connects particle statistics to intrinsic spin: fermions have half-integer spin, bosons integer spin.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <exercises>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-symmetric">
      <statement>
        <p>Write down the symmetric and antisymmetric combinations of two distinguishable quantum states <m>\ket{a}</m> and <m>\ket{b}</m>. Verify that they are eigenstates of the exchange operator with eigenvalues <m>+1</m> and <m>-1</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-probability">
      <statement>
        <p>For two identical fermions in states 1 and 2, calculate the probability density <m>|\Psi(x_1, x_2)|^2</m> for an antisymmetric wavefunction and note how it vanishes on the diagonal <m>x_1 = x_2</m>. Compare with the symmetric (bosonic) case.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-helium">
      <statement>
        <p>For the helium atom (two electrons), write the ground-state Slater determinant in terms of 1s orbitals with spin-up and spin-down states.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-three-fermions">
      <statement>
        <p>Three identical fermions are in single-particle states labeled 1, 2, 3. Write down the correctly antisymmetrized wavefunction as a 3×3 Slater determinant.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-number-operator">
      <statement>
        <p>In Fock space, derive the action of the number operator <m>\hat{n}_i = a_i^\dagger a_i</m> on an occupation state <m>|n_1, n_2, \ldots\rangle</m>. Show that it returns <m>n_i</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch06-advanced">
      <statement>
        <p><em>Challenge.</em> Starting from the fermionic anticommutation relations, show that <m>(a_i^\dagger)^2 = 0</m>, confirming that at most one fermion can occupy each state.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</chapter>
